  "title": "Re-describe the VSM",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8dc38c66c9d44e72",
      "text": "Here I set out to engage personally with the VSM by re-describing the key elements in my own words. These re-framings would give starting points for graphics work."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "25b7e1b860ed8977",
      "text": "# VSM elements\nSee [[the VSM]] for the original versions.\nWe start with SYSTEM 5, for reasons that should become obvious.\n- **[[SYSTEM 5]]** Guardianship - ensuring the continued meaning of our purpose - what we're really doing here. Generally slow and careful as regards implementing change; capable of incisive intervention if critical conditions make this necessary.\n- **[[SYSTEM 4]]** Outside and Future - sensing and feedback with developmental and transformational purpose. Generally learning; questioning, contemplative, discursive, with a duty to clearly formulate insights and instantiate actionable proposals that concretise these.\n- **[[SYSTEM 3]]** Inside and Now - sensing and feedback for effective course correction. Integrating signals from Systems 2, 4 and 5 as the basis for core policy evolution / structure-Preserving Transformation. \n- **[[SYSTEM 2]]** Active Policy Engagement - Sensing, feedback and communications for continuous tactical optimisation. Integrating signals from / between Systems 1 and 3 as the basis for operational policy evolution that brings core policy to life.\n- **[[SYSTEM 1]]** is the minimum instantiation - a complete value production system, with everything it needs; an individual considered as a one-man-band, as it were. Consequently it is a whole VSM in and of itself, performing at this level all of systems 2-5 with the addition of direct value production. Thus System 1, at the base layer of the whole, is represented as two interacting sub-systems:\n  - VALUE PRODUCTION ACTIVITY: The Daily life of making stuff,\n  - CREATIVE CONTROL (SELF-MANAGEMENT): Critical constructive engagement, embedded into process (scale-appropriate implementations of 2,3,4,5)."
    }
